  <h1 class="page-title">Aligning Veteran Recognition for NOAA &amp; USPHS Officers</h1>
  <p class="page-subtitle">Four House bills currently before the House Committee on Government Operations</p>

  <!-- Issue overview -->
  <div class="issue-banner">
    <h2>The Issue</h2>
    <p><a href="https://www.govinfo.gov/content/pkg/USCODE-2011-title38/html/USCODE-2011-title38-partI.htm" target="_blank" rel="noopener">United States Code, Title 38</a> recognizes commissioned officers of the U.S. Public Health Service (USPHS) and the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA) as veterans — but Michigan law does not, creating gaps in recognition and benefits for these officers and their families. Four House bills were introduced and referred to the House Committee on Government Operations in November 2025 to correct this inconsistency.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- The four bills -->
  <div class="section-label">The four bills</div>
  <div class="bill-list">

    <div class="bill-row priority">
      <div class="bill-num">HB 5280 <span class="priority-tag">★ Priority</span></div>
      <div class="bill-body">
        <div class="bill-title">Income Tax Act of 1967 — Retirement Pay Equity</div>
        <div class="bill-desc">Amends Act 281 of 1967 to extend Michigan retirement tax fairness to active duty, retired officers, and surviving spouses of USPHS and NOAA Commissioned Corps. Our primary advocacy target — achieves retirement pay equity without requiring redefinition of the word "veteran."</div>
        <a class="bill-link" href="https://archive.legislature.mi.gov/documents/2025-2026/billintroduced/House/pdf/2025-HIB-5280.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View full bill text ↗</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bill-row">
      <div class="bill-num">HB 5262</div>
      <div class="bill-body">
        <div class="bill-title">Uniformity of Service Dates Act</div>
        <div class="bill-desc">Amends Act 190 of 1965 to include commissioned officers of NOAA and USPHS as a class of veterans, consistent with the federal definition under Title 38 USC.</div>
        <a class="bill-link" href="https://www.legislature.mi.gov/documents/2025-2026/billintroduced/House/pdf/2025-HIB-5262.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View full bill text ↗</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bill-row">
      <div class="bill-num">HB 5278</div>
      <div class="bill-body">
        <div class="bill-title">State Personal Identification Card Act</div>
        <div class="bill-desc">Amends Act 222 of 1972 to add veteran designation on Michigan state ID cards for NOAA and USPHS commissioned officers.</div>
        <a class="bill-link" href="https://www.legislature.mi.gov/documents/2025-2026/billintroduced/House/pdf/2025-HIB-5278.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View full bill text ↗</a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bill-row">
      <div class="bill-num">HB 5279</div>
      <div class="bill-body">
        <div class="bill-title">Michigan Vehicle Code</div>
        <div class="bill-desc">Amends Act 300 of 1949 to add veteran designation on Michigan driver's licenses for NOAA and USPHS commissioned officers.</div>
        <a class="bill-link" href="https://www.legislature.mi.gov/documents/2025-2026/billintroduced/House/pdf/2025-HIB-5279.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">View full bill text ↗</a>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>

  <!-- Focus on HB 5280 -->
  <div class="section-label">Our focus</div>
  <div class="focus-card">
    <h3>Why HB 5280 is our primary target</h3>
    <p>While there is some opposition to the bills that rely on redefining the word "veteran," there is little to no opposition to HB 5280, which achieves retirement pay equity without requiring that redefinition. Our advocacy efforts are therefore concentrated on securing passage of HB 5280. Supporting resources are available below.</p>
